<!-- Auto-logon set via the registry (specialize pass), not the declarative
     <AutoLogon> element: that element was tried first and every deployment
     that included it failed outright during Setup itself with
     "Installation could not be completed", regardless of where in
     oobeSystem it was placed (tested both immediately after UserAccounts
     and immediately before FirstLogonCommands) - narrowed down by
     eliminating every other variable changed around the same time
     (static-vs-DHCP networking, hostname length, the OOBE additions
     below) via controlled, single-variable tests, and confirmed by a real
     deployment completing once <AutoLogon> was removed entirely.

     The commands below write the exact same registry values Windows
     itself would write from a working <AutoLogon> element (Winlogon
     reads these at first-logon time regardless of which mechanism put
     them there). They run via reg.exe, not powershell.exe: a first
     attempt used a single powershell.exe -Command one-liner here and
     that broke Setup a different way, a hard crash immediately after
     landing in specialize ("the computer was unexpectedly restarted, or
     an unexpected error occurred"), consistent with a real, documented
     failure mode where PowerShell cmdlets in RunSynchronousCommand crash
     this early in Setup because WMI/CIM and other subsystems it can
     depend on aren't fully initialized yet (Microsoft Q&A 731439, same
     RunSynchronousCommand/specialize combination, a cmdlet failing with
     WBEM_E_CRITICAL_ERROR for exactly this reason). reg.exe has none of
     that startup dependency, it's one of the small set of tools
     MDT/Packer-style specialize-pass automation reaches for specifically
     because of this fragility. Four separate commands, not one
     semicolon-chained line, because RunSynchronousCommand's Path is a
     single process invocation, not a shell.

     Runs during specialize (system context, so no Credentials needed),
     well before oobeSystem's logon prompt is ever shown, and
     self-contained: no dependency on the OOBE/UserAccounts ordering
     questions investigated (and ruled out) for AutoLogon. AutoLogonCount=1
     mirrors AutoLogon's own LogonCount=1, Windows stops auto-logging in
     once it hits 0. The plaintext password this leaves in the registry is
     scrubbed by the first FirstLogonCommand, same as it was for the
     declarative element - identical exposure window, just a different
     write path getting it there. -->
<component name="Microsoft-Windows-Deployment" processorArchitecture="amd64" publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35" language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS" xmlns:wcm="http://schemas.microsoft.com/WMIConfig/2002/State">
    <RunSynchronous>
{% for cmd in autologon_commands %}
        <RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
            <Description>Set auto-logon registry value {{ loop.index }} of {{ loop.length }}</Description>
            <Order>{{ loop.index }}</Order>
            <Path>{{ cmd }}</Path>
        </RunSynchronousCommand>
{% endfor %}
    </RunSynchronous>
</component>
